content.description: On the steep face, there is a weakness under the small overhang. Start with left hand on chunky knob, and right on good angled ledge. Climb up and to the right. Gain the small ledge with a baby tree. Follow good ledge to arête. See the photo. I'm sure there is a harder sit start.
Sit start with decent feet, a high, small, black crimp with your right hand, and a low, tiny left crimp. Climb straight up on more small crimps, and then exit left to the arete.
content.location: Start about 4-5 feet left of the problem Sounds of Little League.

content.description: Start at slabby moves to the first jug on the northwest arete. This is the first "hard" part. Climb the sharp arete to the first ledge. Continue up the arete to the second ledge. There are a could variations. Once at the second ledge, traverse the summit ridge to the sharp peak.
content.location: Start at the slab to the left of Project.

content.description:
Fun, easy, exposed climbing that spirals up the boulder following a crack/overlap. Turning the corner is exposed, and a fall would be terrible. This could be protected with gear and go at 5.5 or so. 

  Find the obvious overlap on the south side of the boulder. Follow the overlap until it transitions to a crack and turns the corner to an easy topout. If you are feeling brave, continue to the summit point!
content.protection: None. There is a large rock in the fall zone.

content.description: Sit start, and power up the arête. Move up and left using a slopey one foot bar and a thin sidepull. Do a highball top out at 25 feet.
content.location: This ascends the obvious, dark, right arete.

content.description: This is a medium-sized erratic with a few easy highballs and one overhung face.
